WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:09.520
I think the role that I have helped bring to this space is bringing people

00:00:09.520 --> 00:00:14.840
together and so I think through my work at Posit I saw that so many of these

00:00:14.840 --> 00:00:17.920
pharmaceutical companies just wanted to get together they wanted to talk and

00:00:17.920 --> 00:00:22.440
they were coming to me to say can you make these introductions so starting R

00:00:22.440 --> 00:00:25.639
and Pharma was really the spark that brought a lot of the pharmaceutical

00:00:25.639 --> 00:00:30.120
companies together and there for the first time the R Validation Hub had

00:00:30.120 --> 00:00:35.400
their hangout you know ideas around the Pharmaverse were sparked out of the idea

00:00:35.400 --> 00:00:40.099
that these pharmaceutical companies had specific workflows and code that they

00:00:40.099 --> 00:00:44.320
wanted to share so it's been amazing to really just see the life that has come

00:00:44.320 --> 00:00:49.959
out of the R and Pharma conference there was very much this sense and momentum

00:00:49.959 --> 00:00:55.320
that a new horizon was coming out for open source to change the landscape and

00:00:55.320 --> 00:00:58.959
lead to a lot of innovations for clinical trials and so a lot of groups

00:00:58.959 --> 00:01:04.919
that had implemented R for research or for Shiny had now started saying can we

00:01:04.919 --> 00:01:09.000
use this in addition for our late-stage clinical trials work. I could certainly

00:01:09.000 --> 00:01:12.639
feel that there was a change coming to the way that clinical trials were

00:01:12.639 --> 00:01:17.879
conducted in bringing open source to that ecosystem but I knew that it was

00:01:17.879 --> 00:01:20.400
going to take some time and there was going to be a decent amount of change

00:01:20.400 --> 00:01:24.279
management that would have to take place for that to work. Part of the popularity

00:01:24.279 --> 00:01:28.559
of R in the drug development space especially late-stage clinical trials

00:01:28.559 --> 00:01:32.519
is because there was a legacy stat programming language that people had

00:01:32.519 --> 00:01:38.279
used and so migrating from that language to R was a very easy transition for a

00:01:38.279 --> 00:01:42.639
lot of organizations because R is an open source language built for

00:01:42.639 --> 00:01:47.680
statistical computing as well as that legacy code and programming tool was

00:01:47.680 --> 00:01:51.620
also built for stats programming so I think the transition from that previous

00:01:51.660 --> 00:01:56.260
tool to R is natural because languages like Python are more general purpose

00:01:56.260 --> 00:02:00.500
programming languages and so I think that has led to a lot of the adoption in

00:02:00.500 --> 00:02:05.019
the space as well as Shiny I would say. A lot of pharmaceutical companies use our

00:02:05.019 --> 00:02:09.619
professional software for their clinical trials and that typically consists of

00:02:09.619 --> 00:02:13.619
Posit team and Posit team is made up of three different products there's a

00:02:13.619 --> 00:02:17.699
Posit workbench which is the development environment literally it's called a

00:02:17.699 --> 00:02:20.660
development environment because it's where people are going to go in and do

00:02:20.660 --> 00:02:24.699
their programming. There they create software and artifacts and content and

00:02:24.699 --> 00:02:28.419
Shiny apps and workflows and then they move that into production into our

00:02:28.419 --> 00:02:32.020
second product which is called Posit Connect that's the production and

00:02:32.020 --> 00:02:35.979
deployment platform that we host and maintain and then the back-end what's

00:02:35.979 --> 00:02:40.020
surfacing out the production and oftentimes validated packages for both

00:02:40.020 --> 00:02:44.220
of those environments is the Posit package manager and so that's feeding

00:02:44.220 --> 00:02:48.179
packages for reproducibility into the development side as well as feeding

00:02:48.179 --> 00:02:52.380
packages into the production side. Pharmaceutical companies care a lot

00:02:52.380 --> 00:02:57.860
about Posit package manager because there is this great desire to own and

00:02:57.860 --> 00:03:02.179
manage the validation and oftentimes what's referred to as qualification of

00:03:02.179 --> 00:03:05.940
packages and so a lot of work goes internally at pharmaceutical companies

00:03:05.940 --> 00:03:09.779
to say these are the core packages typically around a hundred to two or

00:03:09.779 --> 00:03:13.619
three hundred or so packages that this is what people are going to use for

00:03:13.619 --> 00:03:19.500
clinical trials so package manager specifically is critical for clinical

00:03:19.500 --> 00:03:23.339
development because it makes the source of where their package is coming from

00:03:23.339 --> 00:03:28.380
locked down and approved for the work internally at the company. Yeah there's a

00:03:28.380 --> 00:03:32.500
lot of use cases and companies and pharmaceutical organizations using our

00:03:32.500 --> 00:03:39.259
professional tools. Recently this was highlighted by Satish Murthy in the data

00:03:39.259 --> 00:03:44.179
science hangout that they use Posit package manager for surfacing and

00:03:44.179 --> 00:03:48.699
managing the source of their validated packages that they bring out. That's one

00:03:48.699 --> 00:03:52.740
of the most key things for organizations is to make sure the source of the

00:03:52.740 --> 00:03:58.020
packages coming into the workflows is validated and the right packages. In

00:03:58.020 --> 00:04:01.820
addition to that Merck also had a webinar with us that highlighted their

00:04:01.820 --> 00:04:06.020
use of package manager. There's lots of other organizations that have highlighted

00:04:06.020 --> 00:04:10.779
the use of Posit Connect for where they manage and host their Shiny

00:04:10.779 --> 00:04:14.860
applications. For example Roche and Genentech in their webinar a couple

00:04:14.860 --> 00:04:18.260
months ago highlighted that they have an entire framework that they've built in

00:04:18.260 --> 00:04:23.299
house around Shiny and they host their Shiny apps there with Posit Connect. It's

00:04:23.299 --> 00:04:28.739
going to be interesting to see how the future plays out with introductions to

00:04:28.739 --> 00:04:33.140
new tooling like Python and leading that into AI and how some of that could

00:04:33.140 --> 00:04:35.899
change some of the clinical trials. I don't think that's going to happen right

00:04:35.940 --> 00:04:41.459
away but we see this very big inclusive and interoperable future for drug

00:04:41.459 --> 00:04:43.899
development.

